# Cor.Rules — Antigravity

## Architecture
- Atomic Design ONLY for design-system layer (atoms → molecules → organisms). Do not force on full app.
- Organize app code by feature and concern: features/, hooks/, services/, policies/, validation/, permissions/, route handlers, server actions.
- **Atoms**: smallest indivisible unit (Button, Input, Badge, Spinner).
- **Molecules**: group of atoms forming a coherent unit (Modal, Sheet, SearchBar, FormField).
- **Components**: combination of atoms + molecules into reusable feature elements (ProductCard, AuthForm, DataTable).
- Prefer components under 150 lines. If it exceeds 150, evaluate distinct concerns (data fetching, sub-UI sections, reusable logic) and split at natural boundaries. Never split purely to meet line count.
- Prefer functions under 50 lines. Review anything over 50. Mandatory refactor review at 300+.
- Always extract stateful and business logic into custom hooks.
- One responsibility per component. No hidden logic swamp.

## Security (All 30 enforced)
- Access tokens 15–60 min, refresh tokens rotated + revocable. Absolute session max 7–14 days.
- Never write custom production auth. Use Clerk, Supabase Auth, or Auth0. Enforce MFA.
- Never paste API keys in AI chats. Use process.env. Always.
- .gitignore is file #1, before any application code.
- Rotate secrets every 90 days; immediately on suspected exposure.
- Verify every package before installing. Check npm/PyPI. Check download count + publish date.
- Always request latest stable versions explicitly.
- Run npm audit on every PR; review remediation — no blind audit fix on main.
- Sanitize every input. Use parameterized queries always. Zod/Pydantic at every boundary.
- Enable Row-Level Security from day one.
- No console.log/debug in prod. Structured logging with severity only. Strip debug in client bundles.
- CORS: production domain only. Never wildcard.
- Validate all redirect URLs against a hardcoded allow-list.
- Auth + rate limits on every endpoint including mobile APIs.
- Rate limit by IP + user + endpoint. Stricter for auth/payment/export.
- Password reset: max 3/hr/email + CAPTCHA.
- Cap AI API costs in dashboard AND in code.
- DDoS protection: Cloudflare or Vercel edge config.
- Storage buckets locked per-user. RLS enforced.
- Upload validation by allow-list, size cap (10MB), and content/signature (magic bytes), never extension.
- Verify webhook signatures (Stripe etc.) before processing payment data.
- Resend/SendGrid with SPF/DKIM before any user emails.
- Server-side permission checks always. UI checks are UX, not security.
- Ask AI to act as security engineer and review code before shipping.
- Ask AI to red-team your app. It finds things humans miss.
- Log critical actions: deletions, role changes, payments, data exports.
- Build GDPR account deletion flow before launch.
- Automate backups + test restoration weekly.
- Test and prod fully separate: different DBs, VPCs, keys.
- No test webhooks touching real systems. Use sandbox/test modes.
- CSP + security headers by default (HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy).
- CSRF protection when using cookie sessions (SameSite + CSRF tokens).
- Secrets scanning pre-commit (Gitleaks/detect-secrets) + CI gate.
- Pin dependencies + lockfile discipline. No floating versions.
- Least privilege for all service roles. No god keys in app runtime.

## Agent Behavior
- If a rule must be broken, add `SEC-DEBT: <reason>` comment and explain in PR.
- CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md is a behavior contract, not just a style guide. Operational constraints belong here.
- Enter plan mode for any non-trivial task (3+ steps or architectural decisions).
- After any correction: update rules to prevent recurrence.
- Never mark a task complete without proving it works.
- Autonomous bug fixing: given a bug, fix it. No hand-holding required from user.

## Stack Defaults
- Backend: Python FastAPI > Node.js
- Auth: Firebase > Supabase
- Vector DB: Pinecone > pgvector
- Compute: Render > Vercel (heavy backend), Modal/Lambda > Celery
- Mobile: Expo > bare Xcode
- Inference: ANE → Metal → Colab (never local CPU)
